    body: `The Landscape Before the Break
Our client was a mid-sized construction and infrastructure development company, based in Southern Europe, with a specialization in toll road concessions. They had been operating in a Latin American country for over fifteen years, building and operating a 400-kilometer toll road that connected the country's agricultural interior to its main export port.
The concession agreement was a model of its kind. The client had invested $800 million in construction and maintenance. The government had guaranteed a minimum traffic volume and a regulated toll structure that ensured a reasonable return. For the first ten years, the arrangement worked well. The road was built on time and under budget. Traffic volumes met projections. The client made steady profits. The government collected taxes.
Then the political winds shifted.

The Moment of Rupture

A new government came to power on a platform of economic nationalism. One of its first acts was to review all infrastructure concessions signed by the previous administration. The review was ostensibly about transparency and value for money. In practice, it was about nullifying contracts with foreign companies and transferring assets to state-owned enterprises or local champions.
The client's toll road concession was one of the first to be targeted. The government claimed that the concession had been awarded through irregular means—a claim they never substantiated with evidence. They terminated the agreement unilaterally, seized control of the road, and expelled the client's management team.
The client did what any rational investor would do: they filed for arbitration under the bilateral investment treaty between their home country and the host country. The arbitration was conducted under the rules of the International Centre for Settlement of Investment Disputes (ICSID). It took four years.
The client won. The tribunal awarded them $340 million in damages—compensation for the value of the remaining concession period, the seized assets, and lost profits. The award was binding under international law. The government refused to pay.
Then the government defaulted on its sovereign debt.

The Immediate Fallout

The sovereign default changed everything. Before the default, the client was a creditor with a valid legal claim. After the default, the client was one creditor among many—and far from the largest or most powerful. The IMF came in with a bailout package. Bondholders formed committees to negotiate a restructuring. Bilateral lenders—China, the Paris Club, regional development banks—sat at the table.
The client was not invited to any of these discussions. Their $340 million award was a rounding error compared to the country's $50 billion debt burden. The government offered to settle for 10 cents on the dollar—$34 million. The client refused. The government raised the offer to 15 cents—$51 million. The client's board started to waver. The legal team said wait for enforcement. But enforcement required attaching assets—bank accounts, aircraft, diplomatic properties—and every traditional target had already been stripped or was protected by sovereign immunity.
The client called Parasym Syndicate.

The Intervention

Phase I: The Secondary Market Play

We advised the client to do something most arbitration winners refuse to consider: sell a portion of the award. Not to a vulture fund—the client rejected that on principle, and vulture funds were offering only 15–20 cents on the dollar anyway. Instead, we approached a development finance institution that had an ongoing policy dialogue with the government. The DFI was already negotiating a broader economic reform program. They had leverage that the client did not.
We structured a deal: the DFI would purchase $100 million of the $340 million award for $40 million (40 cents on the dollar). The DFI would then hold the claim, not enforce it immediately, but use it as leverage in their policy negotiations with the government. The government could not afford to alienate the DFI—the DFI was part of the IMF-backed bailout. The DFI, for its part, got a potential return of 150% if the government eventually paid.
The client received $40 million in cash immediately—more than double the government's initial settlement offer. And they retained $240 million of the award, with the DFI now having a shared interest in collecting it.

Phase II: The Non-Traditional Attachment

The traditional methods of enforcing an arbitration award against a sovereign—attaching bank accounts, seizing aircraft, impounding diplomatic property—had all been tried against this government before. The government had responded by moving its assets. Bank accounts were emptied or moved to jurisdictions that did not recognize ICSID awards. Aircraft were re-registered under shell companies. Diplomatic property was declared inviolable.
We needed a non-traditional target. We found one: overflight fees. Commercial airlines pay fees to fly through a country's airspace. These fees are collected by a regional clearinghouse—an international organization that manages air traffic control payments across multiple countries. The clearinghouse was located in a neutral country that did recognize ICSID awards. And the fees passed through the clearinghouse before being remitted to the government.
With a friendly court order in the neutral country, we attached $18 million in overflight fees in a single month. The government did not even know the fees had been attached until the clearinghouse notified them that the payment had been redirected. The government got the message: there was nowhere left to hide.

Phase III: The Structured Settlement

The overflight fee attachment brought the government to the table. But they still could not pay $340 million in cash. The IMF agreement limited their spending. Bondholder negotiations restricted their ability to make preferential payments to individual creditors.
We negotiated a structured settlement: $200 million paid over eight years, backed by a specific revenue stream—port fees, not the general budget. Port fees were collected by a semi-independent port authority, not directly controlled by the finance ministry. The port authority had its own revenue, its own bank accounts, and its own legal personality. It was not subject to the same spending restrictions as the central government.
The structure was complex: the port authority would deduct $25 million per year from its collections and pay it into an escrow account held by a neutral trustee. The trustee would pay the client quarterly. If the port authority failed to pay, the client could attach the port's receivables directly—a simpler enforcement action than attaching sovereign assets.
The government agreed. The DFI, which still held $100 million of the award, agreed to a parallel structure. The client's board approved the settlement unanimously.

The Outcome
● $340 million arbitration award converted into a $200 million structured settlement—a 59% recovery, compared to the 10–15% initially offered.

● $40 million received immediately from the DFI purchase—enough to stabilize the client's balance sheet and fund their next project.

● $18 million attached via overflight fees—enough to bring the government to the table.

● 8-year payment stream secured by port fees, a specific, enforceable revenue source that survives changes in government.

● Client board unanimously approved the settlement after eighteen months of uncertainty.

The client's general counsel told us: "The lawyers won the arbitration. You won the collection. There's a difference, and we learned it the hard way."`,
